ore any new code (YAGNI, then a standard-library primitive, a native platform feature, an installed dependency, a one-line expression and only then minimal custom code); it runs after surface and intent routing and changes neither surface precedence nor the Iron Law. Phase 1.5 is the Code Quality Gate, required before claiming implementation is done. It applies P0, P1 and P2 checks and surface standards. For OPENCODE, this phase includes a comment-hygiene enforcement script that must exit with zero violations. Phase 2 is Debugging: trace one symptom to one root cause at a time, fix it and retest. Phase 3 is Verification: run the surface verification commands, collect fresh evidence and record it.\n\n  Line 145: | Comment-hygiene check blocks commit | A forbidden artifact label exists in a code comment | Run `bash .opencode/skills/sk-code/scripts/check-comment-hygiene.sh <file>` to see the violation. Replace the label with the durable reason instead. |\n\n  Line 180: | Comment hygiene | `bash .opencode/skills/sk-code/scripts/check-comment-hygiene.sh <file>` reports zero violations |\n\n  Line 200: | [`scripts/check-comment-hygiene.sh`](./scripts/check-comment-hygiene.sh) | Phase 1.5 comment-hygiene enforcement |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/universal/code_style_guide.md:\n  Line 175: - Do NOT add `ceiling:` to the comment-hygiene checker's allowed-pattern list. It already passes (it contains no forbidden id), and allow-listing it would let a forbidden id on the same line slip through, because allowed patterns short-circuit violation detection.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/universal/code_quality_standards.md:\n  Line 127: 2. Run the comment-hygiene checker on each modified file before committing:\n\n  Line 129:    .opencode/skills/sk-code/scripts/check-comment-hygiene.sh <file>\n\n  Line 136:    - **CI**: `.github/workflows/comment-hygiene.yml` re-validates on every PR to main; cannot be bypassed with `--no-verify`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.4.0.0.md:\n  Line 25: When a simplification is deliberate — a known shortcut chosen on purpose, not an oversight — it should read as intent. A new convention in `references/universal/code_style_guide.md` §4 introduces a neutral `ceiling:` comment that names the shortcut, its known ceiling, and the upgrade path or trigger. It is a durable WHY, not a brand or tool prefix (a brand prefix reads as a perishable, cargo-cult label), and it is explicitly NOT added to the comment-hygiene checker's allowed-pattern list — it already passes because it carries no forbidden id, and allow-listing it would let a forbidden id on the same line slip through. This is the producer-side companion to the reviewer-side downgrade rule shipped in sk-code-review v1.4.0.0.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.1.0.md:\n  Line 29: - MIT attribution present in both new artifacts and the perf fold-in; comment hygiene clean.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/068-review-record-valid/spec.md:\n  Line 25:     completion_pct: 100\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.5.0.4.md:\n  Line 77: The post-audit cross-check left two follow-ups, and both shipped next. The code-index launcher used to load env, force the maintainer index flags and write stderr at require time, because the entrypoint guard sat below those statements. Importing it now runs no side effects. Its env work moved into a bootstrap function called only when the file is the process entrypoint, and a new test asserts a require leaves the environment untouched. The comment-hygiene checker also grew the patterns it was missing. It now catches RC, single-number DR, hyphen phase and council-seat labels, and it scans inline trailing comments rather than only full-line ones. A blanket F-number pattern stayed out by design because almost all of its matches are function keys and figures.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/resume-ladder.vitest.ts:\n  Line 82:     `    completion_pct: ${options.completionPct ?? 72}`,\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/002-valid-level1/spec.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/002-valid-level1/plan.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/002-valid-level1/tasks.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/002-valid-level1/implementation-summary.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/README.md:\n  Line 22: - The folder contains 18 active rule files spanning gate enforcement, tool routing, CLI dispatch, deep-skill workflow adoption, comment hygiene, memory-system and DB-topology rules, completion verification, deep-review, naming conventions, fable governor constraints, automated-writer safety, regression-baseline discipline, finding verification, recursion control, and causal-graph semantics (see §2 Package Topology). It originated with just `gate-enforcement.md` and `gate-tool-routing.md`.\n\n  Line 38: +-- comment-hygiene.md                            # No ephemeral artifact pointers (ADR/REQ/spec paths) in code comments\n\n  Line 100: +-- comment-hygiene.md                            # No ephemeral artifact pointers (ADR/REQ/spec paths) in code comments\n\n  Line 129: | `comment-hygiene.md` | Never embed spec paths or packet/ADR/REQ/task/finding ids in code comments; keep the durable WHY. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/comment-hygiene.md:\n  Line 24:   - check-comment-hygiene\n\n  Line 25:   - comment hygiene\n\n  Line 70: 1. **Pre-commit gate** — `check-comment-hygiene.sh` runs as a pre-commit hook and fails the commit if any staged file contains forbidden patterns in comments.\n\n  Line 72: 3. **CI gate** — `.github/workflows/comment-hygiene.yml` re-validates on every PR to main; this gate cannot be bypassed with `--no-verify`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/verify-before-completion-claims.md:\n  Line 27: Across long sessions, status was repeatedly stated BEFORE it was true — a commit silently blocked by the comment-hygiene pre-commit gate, a strict-validate that was actually FAILED, a doc Edit that silently failed (\"string not found\") yet was credited in the commit message, a Step-0 boot marked PASS when the daemon had exited with EINVAL, and a fabricated commit hash written into a memory for a commit that never landed. Each was caught only by a later re-check. A false \"done\" is worse than a slow \"done\" because downstream steps build on a state that isn't real. (Owner: \"Report outcomes faithfully\"; \"never claim an unverified commit/file.\")\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/069-review-record-missing-report/spec.md:\n  Line 25:     completion_pct: 100\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/003-valid-level2/spec.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/003-valid-level2/plan.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/003-valid-level2/checklist.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/003-valid-level2/tasks.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/test-fixtures/003-valid-level2/implementation-summary.md:\n  Line 23:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/README.md:\n  Line 65: +-- validation/            # Validation, evidence and comment-hygiene checks\n\n  Line 111: | `validation/` | Contains active validators used by validation flow, pre-commit checks and write-time comment hygiene. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/validation/validation_rules.md:\n  Line 99: **Lifecycle predicate:** strict validation only, with a completion claim present (`checklist.md` checked evidence, `completion_pct: 100`, or complete/shipped status).  \n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/hooks/goal_plugin.md:\n  Line 73: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-code/scripts/check-comment-hygiene.sh .opencode/plugins/mk-goal.js\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/spec/scaffold-debug-delegation.sh:\n  Line 259:     completion_pct: 0\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Envir